MODEL: opus

User wants next-level design for task and plan files. Keep .md as the source of truth (portable, LLM-friendly, human-readable) but give it typed components — like Markdoc (Stripe) or Portable Text — that resolve against live SQLite state at render time.

INVOKE /doey-masterplan — this is strategic design territory with many decisions to make. Mandatory interview phase, ultrathink research, vertical phase design.

CORE VISION:
- .md file = source of truth for tasks and plans
- Thin typed-tag layer embedded in the Markdown: progress, phase, cluster, task-ref, file-ref, proof, decision, risk (starter set — design the full schema)
- Parser produces an AST → pure-function renderers per consumer:
  * Go TUI task detail view (rich blocks, progress bars, collapsible sections, clickable file refs)
  * CLI doey task show (ANSI rendering)
  * Raw .md viewer (tags degrade to literal text)
  * Commit message composer (structured decisions + proofs footer)
  * LLM context builder (resolves task-refs to live summaries, avoids dead IDs)
  * Popup viewer from task 479 (now has more to render)
- Tags resolve live: task-ref id=550 pulls current status/title/team from SQLite at render time — zero staleness
- Queryable AST: all risks with severity=high across phase P2, all file-refs to path X, etc.
- Bidirectional traceability: file-ref from a task creates a reverse index, code ↔ plan coupling

RESEARCH QUESTIONS FOR PHASE 1 (masterplan interview + ultrathink):
1. Syntax — Markdoc ({% tag %}), MyST directives (:::), CommonMark generic directives, or custom? Tradeoffs for LLM readability, git diff quality, parser complexity.
2. Schema location — in-code registry, YAML file, JSON schema, or inline in tag definitions? How does it version?
3. Renderer architecture — single Go package with visitor pattern, or plugin-per-consumer? How is TUI integration done without coupling taskdoc to bubble tea?
4. Live resolution — at render time (always fresh, slower) or at write time (cached, can go stale)? Hybrid?
5. Backward compatibility — existing tasks 1-552 must still work unchanged. Migration path: opt-in, auto-migrate, or deprecation?
6. Plans vs tasks — do plans get a different tag set or the same one? How do plans embed tasks (by id, by include, by query)?
7. Tag set MVP — which 6-10 tags ship first? Starter: progress, phase, cluster, task-ref, file-ref, proof, decision, risk. What else?
8. LLM context builder integration — this is the highest leverage consumer. How do we shrink task-ref resolution from full task dump to optimal context?
9. Query language — do we need one (e.g. taskdoc-query, JQ-like), or is the AST enough?
10. Editing UX — can users still hand-edit tags in any .md editor? Do we need a linter/LSP?
11. Storage — do rendered outputs get cached? Where?
12. Testing — how do we unit-test tag resolution and renderers? Property tests on the AST?

VERTICAL PHASES (rough — masterplan refines):
P0. Design interview + ultrathink research — syntax choice, schema design, architecture sketch, risk list
P1. MVP parser + schema registry + 4 starter tags (progress, task-ref, file-ref, proof)
P2. CLI renderer (doey task show --rich) + raw .md fallback
P3. TUI detail renderer (plugs into existing task detail view + popup from 479)
P4. LLM context builder integration (Worker brief packs resolve task-refs live)
P5. Full tag set (phase, cluster, decision, risk, + extras) + query API
P6. Plans — plan.md files, phase composition, reverse index
P7. Migration tooling + linter/LSP + docs
P8. Fresh-install proof, doey doctor integration

CONSTRAINTS:
- Must not break any of the 552 existing tasks
- Must work with fresh install (no local-only state)
- Bash 3.2 / macOS portability rules apply
- Go package lives in tui/internal/taskdoc/
- No new heavy deps if avoidable — parse on top of existing Goldmark if already present, otherwise hand-rolled
- LLM context quality is a KEY metric — must measurably shrink worker brief size while keeping information density

DELIVERABLE:
A masterplan document (plan.md) with:
- Design decisions per research question above
- Chosen syntax with rationale
- Tag schema registry (initial set)
- Renderer architecture diagram
- Phased rollout plan (P0-P8 or refined)
- Risk register
- Success metrics (LLM context shrinkage, user adoption, zero breakage)
- One hand-written example: a real existing task (e.g. 551) translated to the new format, rendered as CLI output

The masterplan goes through Architect and Critic review loop before Boss sees it.
